    "15": {
      "answer": "No, the moving average model is not always causal. A MA(q) model is causal because it depends only on present and past errors. But it is not always invertible. For a MA model to be invertible, the roots must be outside the unit circle. If this condition fails, we cannot write it as an AR model, so it is not invertible.",
      "answered_at": "2026-05-09T14:41:13.702Z",
      "date": "2026-05-09",
      "time": "16:41:13"
    },
    "16": {
      "answer": "Exponential Smoothing means that recent observations have more weight than older ones in the forecast. The weights decrease exponentially as we go back in time. In exponential smoothing, we use a smoothing parameter (alpha) between 0 and 1. This parameter controls how much weight we give to recent data versus past data. A high alpha means we focus more on recent values, while a low alpha gives more importance to historical data.",
      "answered_at": "2026-05-09T14:41:13.702Z",
      "date": "2026-05-09",
      "time": "16:41:13"
    }
